<HEADLINE> FPDA Defense Ministers to Visit Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Defense Ministers from the Five
Power Defense Arrangements (FPDA) members will visit Kuala Lumpur,
Malaysia, Sunday, as part of the program for the 4th FPDA Defense
Ministers' meeting to be held in Singapore on July 4, according to
a press release by Singapore's Ministry of Defense Saturday.
</P>
<P>
They include Singapore Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for
Defense Tony Tan, Australian Defense Minister John Moore,
Malaysian Defense Minister Dato' Sri Mohamed Najib bin Tun Haji
Abdul Razak, New Zealand's Defense Minister Mark Burton and
British Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State of Defense Lewis
Moonie.
</P>
<P>
During their one-day stay at the capital of Malaysia, Dato' Sri
Mohamed Najib bin Tun Haji Abdul Razak will give them a dinner.
They will call on Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamed.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will officiate at the opening ceremony of
Exercise Flying Fish 2000 at Tuas Naval Base in the southwest of
the Singapore island after visit to Malaysia and then attend the
meeting to be chaired by Tony Tan. They will also call on
Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong.
</P>
<P>
The FPDA groups Australia, Malaysia, New Zealand, Singapore and
the United Kingdom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
