<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Environmentalists Decide to Evacuate Penguins From Polluted Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Western Cape Nature
Conservation Board decided on Saturday evening to begin evacuating
the entire colony of 55,000 penguins from Dassen Island on Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The penguins will be taken by boat to Yzerfontein about 60
kilometers from Cape Town on the Cape west coast, spokeswoman for
the South African National Foundation for the Conservation of
Coastal Birds Christina Pretorius said.
</P>
<P>
Some penguins affected by last Friday's oil spill from the bulk
oil carrier, Treasure, were already being evacuated on Saturday,
Western Cape deputy-director of disaster management Schalk
Carstens said.
</P>
<P>
The remaining penguins had been fenced in to prevent them
leaving the island and entering the sea after oil from the sunken
Treasure encircled the island.
</P>
<P>
An aerial picture taken in the vicinity of the island on Friday
showed that strong sea currents and the wind appeared to be
causing the oil slick to drift past the island.
</P>
<P>
Slightly more than 1,200 penguins have so far been taken off
Dassen Island and were being rehabilitated in Salt River.
</P>
<P>
Pretorius said 400 penguin chicks were being cared for at a
private sanctuary in Melkbosstrand on the Cape West coast where
they would be hand- fed and reared. Another 94 chicks were being
cared for in a separate facility in Milnerton.
</P>
<P>
A third batch of 160 penguins was trucked overnight on
Thursday to Port Elizabeth and released into the sea in Algoa Bay
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to environmentalists, the birds made straight for
the sea to begin their long swim back to Robben Island, expected
to take about 10 days, by which time authorities have to clear the
coastline, Robben Island and Dassen Island beaches of the heavy
fuel oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
