<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oman GDP Up 10.4 Percent in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Oman's GDP witnessed a 10.4
percent in 1999 against 10.2 percent in 1998, said an annual report
issued by the Central Bank of Oman on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The rise in GDP was attributed to the increase in earnings from
the energy, crude and natural gas sectors, which accounted for 38.7

percent of the GDP in 1999, while non-oil sectors, agriculture and
services, dropped by 2.2 percent, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the actual deficit in the state budget rose
from 375.3 million rials (975.78 million U.S. dollars) in 1998 to
465.8 million rials (1.21 billion dollars) in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the public expenditure rose by 1.9
percent to 2,264.1 million rials (5.89 billion dollars) in 1999
from 2,221.6 million rials (5.78 billion dollars) in 1998, because
of a 2.5 percent increase in current expenses, while investment
expenses fell by four percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
