<HEADLINE> Cyprus President Leaves For Geneva to Attend Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides
Sunday afternoon left here for Geneva to attend the third round of
U.N.-sponsored proximity talks on Cyprus, due to start on July 5.
</P>
<P>
On their way to Geneva, Clerides and his company will stop in
Athens to meet with Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis and members
of the Greek government.
</P>
<P>
According to local media, Clerides will have a meeting with U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan in Geneva on July 5.
</P>
<P>
Then the talks will be continued with the Secretary-General's
Special Adviser for Cyprus Alvaro de Soto.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Turkish Cypriots-controlled north
and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when Turkey
invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of proximity talks under the U.N. auspices between
President Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash have
already been held to prepare the ground for substantive
negotiations leading to a comprehensive settlement for the Cyprus
issue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before his departure at Larnaca airport, Cyprus'
southern coast, Clerides repeated the position that the Greek
Cypriot side "does not accept the confederation" as a solution to
the Cyprus issue, but would "negotiate within the framework set out
by the U.N. resolution."
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots are seeking a confederation of two "
states", although their breakaway republic, unilaterally declared
in 1983, is not recognized internationally.  
</P>
</TEXT>
