<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC States Called to Revise Investment Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Some existing Gulf laws which
hinder residents from investing in the six Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) countries need to be revised, according to a latest study
released by the United Arab Emirates' Industry Bank.
</P>
<P>
Opportunities must be created to attract back part of the Gulf
investments abroad to help diversify investments and contribute to
GCC economic and social development, the study stressed.
</P>
<P>
It said that channels in which expatriate residents are allowed
to invest are extremely limited and a revision of the laws will
help them retain their savings in the region.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the traditional and services sectors in which GCC
national capital is preferred, the industrial and IT segments can
be opened to Gulf expatriates for investment, the study suggested.
</P>
<P>
Moves taken to benefit from remittances of GCC-based expatriates
and investments in the local private sectors remain limited,
although the GCC states are working hard to attract foreign
investments, it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The study said foreign investments in the Gulf, excluding the
oil sector, were estimated at 15 billion U.S. dollars, and
remittances by expatriates at 18 billion dollars in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Several GCC countries introduced measures recently to encourage
foreign investments, it noted. In Bahrain, crucial amendments were
made in the Companies Law for 100 percent foreign ownership.
</P>
<P>
Last April, Saudi Arabia introduced a system allowing full
foreign ownership of firms, property ownership, and trading in the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance established
in 1981, groups Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the
UAE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
