<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Security Threat to U.S. Targets in Jordan: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdel Ilah
Khatib said here on Sunday that he saw no security threats to
American targets in the kingdom although the U.S. embassy in Amman
cancelled its Independence day celebrations slated for July 4.
</P>
<P>
"I do not see any logic behind the cancellation," Khatib said
in an interview with Xinhua, adding the government has confidence
in the security and intelligence services of the kingdom to protect
all foreign missions in the capital.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that it was up to the U.S. embassy to
decide whether to hold the national day reception or not, and the
mission had informed his ministry of the cancellation in advance.
</P>
<P>
The celebration is held each year at the U.S. ambassador's
residence in Amman, and is attended by hundreds of Jordanian
dignitaries and representatives from other diplomatic missions.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. embassy decided last Thursday to cancel the event
because of what it called a "terrorist targeting" of the embassy
and other possible American targets in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
It also warned American citizens travelling in the kingdom to
keep a low profile and to take extra prudence.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian officials had played down the U.S. warning and
described it as "routine alerts" issued by U.S. embassies in most
regions of the world, and there was nothing new in terms of threats
to justify such a statement in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Similar warnings were issued by the U.S. embassy in Amman last
December, when Jordanian police rounded up 14 suspected terrorists
who allegedly sneaked into the kingdom on forged travel documents
to sabotage new millenium celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian authorities said the suspects, believed to be linked
to Afghanistan-based Saudi-expelled billionaire Osma bin Laden, had
planned to attack American and Israeli targets during the new year
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Bin Laden is one of the most wanted suspects by Washington,
which has accused him of masterminding the 1998 bombings of the U.
S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, killing over 200 people.
</P>
<P>
However, no serious attacks on American targets were reported in
Jordan in recent memory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
