<HEADLINE> Two Men Arrested for Manslaughter in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian police have arrested two
people from a company that has imported a radioactive object
fatally poisoning a father and a son, and charged them with
manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
The two people are identified as Salim Sayyed Ahmed, 47, the
owner of a pipe welding firm and a 36-year-old engineer working for
him, Rifaat Mohammed Ali, the Middle East News Agency reported on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Public prosecutors in the town of Qalyub, north of Cairo, near
the village of Mit Halfa where the deaths occurred, announced the
charges on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The firm had imported the radioactive object, which Mohammed
Abdelrahman Salama, president of Egypt's Atomic Security Authority,
said was iridium 192, from the United States and used it to check
the fastness of gas pipe joints.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutors accused the two men of neglect for leaving the
object at their worksite and failure to inform authorities that it
had gone missing, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Fadl Hassan Fadl, a 61-year-old farmer, found the radioactive
object and took it home. He and his nine-year-old son died in June
from exposure to the object while five more family members have
been treated in hospital.
</P>
<P>
But Egypt's Atomic Energy Authority said in a report issued on
Thursday that it suspected the object had been dumped illegally to
avoid paying 5,000 Egyptian pounds (about 1,500 U.S. dollars), the
fees charged to dispose of radioactive waste at its site. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
