<DOCNO> XIE20000702.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe Urges Zimbabweans To Unite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Sunday urged Zimbabweans to jealously guard the national unity.
</P>
<P>
Such unity was achieved in 1987 following the signing of an
accord between the Zimbabwe African National Union-Patriotic Front
(Zanu-pf) led by Mugabe and the Zimbabwe African People's Union
(Zapu) headed by the late Vice-President Joshua Nkomo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the memorial service of Nkomo who died on July 1
last year, Mugabe said there were some people and organizations
bent on dividing the nation, by referring to the pre-unity civil
conflict in Matabeleland and Midlands provinces in west Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"There are those who want to continue using the quarrel as a
basis for organizing, if not disorganizing the people. What is
the purpose that we fight again? That we divide the people?" he
asked.
</P>
<P>
The president, whose party lost most of the seats in
Matabeleland during last week's parliamentary election, recently
accused the opposition Movement for Democratic Change (MDC) and
some church leaders of fanning division in the region, resulting
in the loss.
</P>
<P>
"Let's look at our past and try to see why the unity accord
came about," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have had a difference, a quarrel, we engaged ourselves in a
 reckless and unprincipled fight," he said, on the fighting that
took place in Matabeleland between 1983 and 1987.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said he and Nkomo looked at the situation at that time
and saw that the "quarrel" had caused untold suffering to the
people, hence the signing of the unity accord.
</P>
<P>
"It was an act of madness, we killed each other and destroyed
each other' s property. It was wrong and both sides were to
blame," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe stressed there was no reason for dissidents to have
rebelled nor was there a reason for the government to use
excessive force to control the situation resulting in the deaths
of innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
He said there was need to examine the adverse effects that were
caused by the fighting and try to correct them.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 people, including Vice-President Joseph Msika,
government ministers and opposition party leaders, attended the
memorial service held at Nkomo's family residence in west
Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
