<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Facilitation Team to Meet Mandela on Peace Protocols </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The facilitation team on
Burundi peace talks is to meet the mediator, former South African
President Nelson Mandela on July 10 in Johannesburg to brief him
on peace protocols.
</P>
<P>
Judge Mark Bomani, head of the team, told journalists in
Tanzania's northern town of Arusha on Saturday that they will
also discuss with the facilitator subsequent programs for various
activities in the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The team, he said, has been revising the draft peace proposals,
 " updating them to take into account response of various parties
during the last few weeks".
</P>
<P>
"We're in advanced stages in the negotiations and we're
positively on course," said Bomani.
</P>
<P>
All 19 parties participating the talks have submitted their
inputs on the draft peace deal text, including a breakaway armed
rebel group CNDD-FDD (the National Defense Council of
Democracy-the Defense Force of Democracy), which submitted its
ideas last week.
</P>
<P>
However, Bomani declined to disclose the contents of FDD's
proposals.
</P>
<P>
He said his team is still waiting for draft proposals from
another rebel group FLN (the National Liberation Force), a
splinter group of PALIPEHUTU (the Hutu People's Liberation
Party), to complete all protocols.
</P>
<P>
Although not yet formalized, an agreement aimed at ending the
violence that has resulted in the deaths of at least 200,000
people, centers on the creation of a transitional government, the
integration of Hutu rebels into the Tutsi-dominated army and an
electoral system that will ensure power- sharing between the
minority Tutsis and majority Hutus.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of violence in Burundi was set off in October
1993, when Tutsi paratroopers assassinated Melchior Ndadaye, a
Hutu who had won the country's first democratic elections four
months earlier.
</P>
<P>
The Arusha negotiations began in July 1998. Last year, Mandela
replaced the late Tanzanian President Julius Nyerere as mediator
and invited all the Hutu rebel groups that had been previously
excluded to take part in the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
