<HEADLINE> Namibian President Urges African Countries to Support Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Namibian President Sam Nujoma
Sunday urged African governments to support the development of
private sector by creating conductive environment.
</P>
<P>
Opening the 24th annual Dar es Salaam International Trade fair,
the visiting Namibian president said the small and medium
enterprises must be promoted because they create employment
opportunities for the majority of people and subsequently improve
their living standard.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma also called on African leaders to promote trade among
themselves and share experiences on ways to improve their
economies.
</P>
<P>
African countries are faced with the challenge of laying
strategies to utilize the abundant unexploited wealth to improve
their economies and ensure that they do no lag behind other
countries in the race of science and technology, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Africa is the richest of all continent, with vast unexploited
minerals and virgin agricultural land," said Nujoma, stressing
that the untapped wealth should be used in promoting economic
development of the continent.
</P>
<P>
He said the Dar es Salaam trade fair provides a place for the
display of products from different parts in the world. It offers
information to consumers and an opportunity for interaction
between exhibitors and visitors.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma, who arrived in Dar es Salaam on Saturday for a
three-day state visit, also pledged his country's commitment to
promote the existing good political and socio-economic relations
with Tanzania and called for more intimate trade ties between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
This year's Dar es Salaam trade fair has attracted more than
1,000 local and foreign companies from 35 countries. It is
expected to end next Sunday.
</P>
