<HEADLINE> Israel, India Seek Closer Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Israel and India have agreed to
establish a diplomatic and security dialogue to further boost their
bilateral ties established eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
During the talks between visiting Indian Foreign Minister
Jaswant Singh and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Foreign
Minister David Levy on Sunday, the leaders of both countries
discussed ways to cement ties in a spectrum of fields including
trade, weaponry as well as science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Levy also called on his Indian counterpart to join in the
efforts of fighting for the release of the 10 Jews convicted and
sentenced to prison terms by an Iranian court over espionage
charges.
</P>
<P>
Singh arrived in Israel Friday on a four-day visit. It is the
first visit of the Indian foreign minister to the Jewish state
since the two nations established diplomatic relations in 1992.
</P>
<P>
According to trade officials in Singh's entourage, the
Indian-Israeli trade is standing at one billion U.S. dollars with
an annual 46-percent growth rate. The trade ties are particularly
marked by the fact that the two countries control 95 percent of the
diamond cutting and polishing industry in the world. 
