<HEADLINE> Egypt, Libya to Resume Air Flights by This Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- EgyptAir, the national carrier of
Egypt, will resume flights to Libya this month after a hiatus of
eight years, an official of the airline said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The development comes following intervention of the two
countries' leaders, aimed at the resumption of flights, initially
scheduled for April 1999, the official was quoted as saying by
Egypt's Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The delay for more than one year was caused by technical and
commercial problems, the official said on condition of anonymity.
He added that three return flights in a week will be organized in
the last 10 days of July, including two between Cairo and Tripoli
and one between Cairo and Benghazi.
</P>
<P>
A delegation from EgyptAir will head for Tripoli in the coming
days to make the final preparations for the resumption of flights
and discussion of re-opening EgyptAir offices in Libya, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
An international air embargo imposed on Libya in April 1992 was
suspended last year after Libya's handover of two Libyans suspected
of
the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland,
which killed 270 people. 
</P>
