<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are the economic briefs
in the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Officials of Iran and the Netherlands here on Sunday
signed two agreements to strengthen cooperation in fisheries and
environment protection.
</P>
<P>
Under the first agreement, the Netherlands will facilitate
Iran's export of fishery products, especially shrimp, to European
markets and Iran will in return increase imports from the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The second agreement calls for the expansion of cooperation in
environment protection in line with concerned international
conventions and principles.
</P>
<P>
It further provides that the Dutch Ministry of Agricultural,
Nature Management and Fisheries will assign an agriculture attache
at the Dutch embassy in Tehran to specify, manage and implement
agricultural and environment projects.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's non-oil exports reached some 621 million U.S.
dollars in the first quarter of the current year (started March
20), a 23.8 percent decline compared to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to figures from the customs department, exports of
agricultural, mineral and industrial products registered the
largest scale of decline, down 34.6 percent, 24 percent and 23.9
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Imports to Iran valued at 3.31 million dollars in the first
quarter, which was 5.6 percent lower than the figure last year.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The trade deficit of Egypt dropped to 2.33 billion U.S.
dollars in the first quarter this year, compared to 3.08 billion
dollars in the same period last year, said a monthly report issued
on Sunday by the Cabinet Information and Decision Support Center.
</P>
<P>
The total exports rose to 1.12 billion dollars in the first
three months of 2000 from 788.12 million dollars in the same period
of 1999, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The imports fell by 420 million dollars to 3.45 billion dollars
between last January and March.
</P>
<P>
Raw materials and cotton exports declined to 134.2 million
dollars in January to March this year from 158.55 million dollars
in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Manufactured and semi-manufactured exports increased to 499.13
million dollars in the first quarter this year from 395.94 million
in January to March last year.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's foreign currency reserves dropped to 15 billion
U.S. dollars in March from 18.9 billion dollars in the same period
last year, said a monthly report issued on Sunday by the Cabinet
Information and Decision Support Center.
</P>
<P>
The figure in March also showed a decline of 10 million dollars
from February and 20 million dollars from January.
</P>
<P>
Domestic liquidity rose to 247.4 billion Egyptian pounds (71.71
billion dollars) in March, compared to 227.5 billion pounds (65.94
billion dollars) in the same month last year. And money supply
amounted to 48.3 billion pounds (14 billion dollars) in March
from 47.8 billion pounds (13.86 billion dollars) in the
corresponding period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
