<HEADLINE> Two Palestinian Officials React to Barak's Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Police Chief Al-Ghazy Al-
Gabaly has said the Palestinian people are ready to defend their
territories in case of any Israeli reaction to the unilateral
proclamation of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian people, who have a long history of revolutions
and struggle, will stand against any Israeli reaction", Al-Ghazy, a
member of the Central Committee of the Palestinian Liberation
Organization, said during the Central Committee meetings which
started in Gaza Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
The meetings will discuss the declaration of the Palestinian
state during the two-day meetings.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said a few days ago that in
case of the unilateral declaration of the Palestinian state, Israel
will start to control new Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Al-Gabaly expressed his hope that Israel will not think of this
mistaken decision which might cost it dearly as it can not have
forgotten the Palestinian intifada.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians are unanimous in the issue of declaring the
Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its capital, he said, pointing
out this will crown the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians are able to defend their territories against
the Israeli potential invasion to bar the declaration of the state,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Azzam al-Ahmad, the Palestinian Minister of Works and
a member of the Central Committee, crossed his fingers that the
declaration of the Palestinian sovereignty will be made within an
agreed-upon framework with Israeli so as to head off many problems.
</P>
<P>
Efforts can be intensified for reaching an agreement on the
outstanding disputes before the end of the Palestinian-Israeli
negotiations after a couple of months, the minister requested.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians believe that they are entitled to have an
independent state proclaimed no later than September 13, a self-
imposed deadline for the Palestinians and Israel to reach a final
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The declaration of the Palestinian state is contingent upon the
Israeli, Arab and international position, said Azzam, reiterating
that the declaration can be delayed for weeks if an agreement with
Israel is in sight.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Israeli threats against the declaration, the
minister said "It seems that it is the anti-peace hard-line trend
in Israel which is the decision-maker."
</P>
<P>
He said "Barak has never forgotten his long-standing bloody
history." Israel's military preparations in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip indicate the coming stage will witness confrontations, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli forces in the occupied Palestinian territories have
recently been provided with more heavy weapons. The security in
Israeli settlements has also been tightened, according to official
Palestinian sources.
</P>
<P>
The Central Committee meetings were attended by the majority of
members from diverse groups of the PLO.
</P>
<P>
PLO Executive Committee Chairman Yasser Arafat delivered a
speech on the latest political developments during the meetings.
The meetings will also discuss a report on the outcomes of the
Palestinian-Israeli negotiations and means of effectuating the PLO
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The meetings were boycotted by the two Islamic Hamas and Jihad
movements which are opposed Oslo Agreement, even though they were
invited to attend the meetings.
</P>
<P>
It is no secret that Hamas spiritual leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin
had attended the Committee meetings held late April 1999 as an
observer. At the time, the committee decided to put the declaration
of the Palestinian state on the back burner as the date of the
Israeli elections was near. 
</P>
</TEXT>
