<HEADLINE> Iran Satisfied with Tehran-Cairo Cooperation: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Foreign Ministry spokesman
Hamid Reza Asefi Sunday expressed his country's satisfaction with
cooperation with Egypt but denied a report on resumption of full
relations soon.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Egypt have had good cooperation in the cultural,
economic and international spheres and such cooperation has gained
momentum in recent months, Asefi was quoted by the Islamic Republic
News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the factors bringing the two countries closer include
the stances taken by Egypt against Israel's refusal to join the
international disarmament treaty and against the Jewish regime's
expansionist policies in the region.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman denied, however, Iran and Egypt are to resume full
diplomatic relations in the near future, as reported by Reuters on
June 30.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Iran's Deputy Foreign Minister Mohammad
Hussein Adeli as saying in Switzerland that the two countries have
a plan to announce the official resumption of full diplomatic
relations in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official had not referred to a specific date for the
resumption of Tehran-Cairo ties and the news report had misquoted
him on the issue, Asefi said.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Egypt severed their diplomatic relations after the 1979
Islamic revolution as Tehran was not satisfied with Cairo's peace
accord with Israel, a country that Iran does not recognize.
</P>
<P>
However, with the foreign policy of detente advocated by Iran's
moderate President Mohammad Khatami, Iran and Egypt have markedly
improved bilateral relations and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
On June 21, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak made a telephone
call to Iranian President Khatami to congratulate Iran on its new
membership in the Group 15 (G15) developing countries.
</P>
<P>
As it was the first such top-contact between the two countries
in 21 years of strained relations, many people considered it a
prelude to the full resumption of ties.
</P>
<P>
Officials and media of both countries highly praised this
contact, expressing hope that the two countries may exchange
ambassadors soon.
</P>
<P>
However, if the two countries are to really resume relations,
some obstacles have to be overcome.
</P>
<P>
Cairo cannot accept a full restoration of ties until Iran re-
names a Tehran street named in honor of former Egyptian president
Sadat's principal assassin, Khaled Islamboli.
</P>
<P>
Islamic hard-liners in Iran also oppose reconciliation with
Egypt, a major U.S. ally in the region. They insist that Egypt must
demolish the tomb of former Iranian Shah, who got shelter from
Egypt after the Islamic revolution and died in Cairo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
