<HEADLINE> Poverty Blocking Anti-AIDS Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy President
Jacob Zuma on Sunday blamed poverty for hindering the fight
against HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"Here in our own continent we are seeing we need an African
solution to the problem," he told a top-level conference of United
States and South African government officials, law-makers and
scientists in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference, prior to the international AIDS
conference in Durban this week, is addressing issues of substance
abuse, crime, violence and HIV/AIDS resulting from poverty.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said many South Africans were driven by poverty to
disregard the accepted wisdom on avoiding HIV infection.
</P>
<P>
The biggest challenge facing South Africa and most developing
countries was the eradication of poverty, Zuma said.
</P>
<P>
As long as poverty and dependence rendered South Africa's women
and children defenceless, and ignorance prevented the rest of the
society from recognizing that their actions counted in the fight
against HIV/AIDS, "our society will not be free of this scourge",
he said.
</P>
<P>
While it was scientifically accepted that HIV/AIDS knew no
social, gender or racial boundaries, it was a fact that the virus
was to be found in greater concentration among the poorer sections
of society, Zuma said.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Dr Manto Tshabalala-Msimang said it was
estimated one in 10 South Africans was infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
But the government had allocated 75 million rand (about 1.1
million U.S. dollars) to fighting the scourge, she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
