<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruling Ugandan Movement Achieves Landslide Win in National Referendum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Ugandan National
Resistance Movement has won the overwhelming majority of votes
cast in the June 29 referendum, which has determined that Uganda
will continuously adopt the Movement System as the nation's
political system.
</P>
<P>
The Movement System attracted 4.322 million votes, accounting
for 90.7 percent of the total, while the Multiparty drew only
442,823 votes, registering at 9.3 percent, announced Flora
Nkuruicenda, deputy chairperson of the National Election
Commission, at the International Conference Center in the capital
Kampala Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The final polling results show that a total of 4.914 million
Ugandans cast their votes at 16,498 polling stations across the
country, accounting for 51.1 percent of the 9.609 million
registered voters.
</P>
<P>
According to the Constitution and Referendum Act, the
referendum was held for Ugandans to choose the Multiparty System
or the Movement System, under which they want to be governed.
</P>
<P>
More than 75 observers from locally based foreign embassies and
overseas monitored the referendum. They were from over 15
countries and regional organizations, including Austria, Belgium,
Britain, the United States, Germany, the Netherlands, Denmark,
South Africa, Kenya, Japan, Indonesia as well as the Organization
of Africa Unity (OAU) and European Community.
</P>
<P>
"The referendum was conducted in an atmosphere of peace and
marked by a high degree of transparency, and the people of Uganda
are of maturity, patience and discipline," said the OAU observers
after they observed all the polling activities including relevant
administrative arrangements in eight districts in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The NGO observers were generally satisfied with the conduct of
the voting, and the people were free to vote for their chosen
political system. Ugandans were able to vote peacefully and free
from intimidation," Canon Grace Kaiso, national co-ordinator of
Non-government-organization Monitoring Cluster, told a press
conference here Saturday .
</P>
<P>
The monitoring cluster of the Referendum 2000 NGO Consortium
has monitored the referendum for the last five months. On the
polling day, they deployed 7,213 observers throughout the country
who witnessed voting in 10, 115 of the 16,498 polling stations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the statement by Donor Referendum 2000 Group said,
"the voting itself appeared to be conducted in a peaceful and
orderly fashion. However, the Group has concluded that the
referendum campaign as a whole was not conducted on a level
playing field."
</P>
<P>
Resources available to the ruling Movement were substantially
larger than those available to pro-multiparty advocates, said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The Movement's success was attributed to the political
stability, as well as social and economic progress since it came
to power in 1986, observers here said.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan Constitution defines the Movement Political System
as broad- based, inclusive and non-partisan, which features the
participatory democracy, transparency, accessibility to all
positions of leadership by all citizens, and individual merit as
a basis for election to political offices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
