<HEADLINE> Seven Burnt to Death in Taxi Accident in East S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Seven people were burnt to
death when a taxi they were travelling in caught fire after
colliding with a car in east South Africa's KwaZulu-Natal Province
on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
Provincial traffic spokesman Vijen Murugan said the accident
happened at around 2 a.m. when the taxi transporting people from a
church meeting in the town of KwaNdengezi collided head-on with
another car.
</P>
<P>
The taxi caught fire and it spread rapidly to the interior.
</P>
<P>
Murugan said seven people, including the driver, were consumed
by the flames and 13 others suffered serious burns and were taken
to nearby hospitals where some of them were reported to be in a
serious condition.
</P>
<P>
Murugan said evidence gathered at the scene strongly suggested
that the taxi was travelling on the wrong lane.
</P>
<P>
The other car was extensively damaged.
</P>
<P>
An intensive investigation into the accident had been launched.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
