<HEADLINE> S. African Presidential AIDS Panel Gears up for Discussions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The South African Presidential
AIDS Advisory Panel on Sunday geared up for its final round of
meetings scheduled for Monday and Tuesday to prepare a report on
the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
"We expect these debates and discussions to be as robust as
they were the first time," President of the South African National
Research Foundation Khotso Mokhele told reporters in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
He said information would be distilled from discussions, and a
report would be formulated and presented to President Thabo
Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki set up the panel to test assumptions about AIDS and
advise the government on how to fight the disease.
</P>
<P>
The panel is made up of more than 30 scientists enlisted by
South Africa, who are evenly split between experts questioning the
link between HIV and AIDS and those subscribing to the
conventional view.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki has come under fire in recent months for reportedly
saying that he was not convinced that HIV was the single virus
causing AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Mokhele said the argument surrounding the divergent views on
the causes of AIDS was very much "alive not for the purpose of
intellectual debate" but to help the government form appropriate
programs and policies to deal with the pandemic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
