<HEADLINE> S. Africa Clamps Down on Police Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The South African Police
Services (SAPS) has launched a crackdown on police corruption to
ensure a clean police force in the fight against rampant crimes.
</P>
<P>
In northeast South Africa's Mpumalanga Province alone, the
operation has nabbed at least 32 police officers on fraud-related
incidents since the beginning of the year, the South African Press
Association reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted provincial police spokesman Senior
Superintendent Theo du Bruyn as saying a six-member police
anti-corruption unit was probing fraud allegations against
another 193 policemen.
</P>
<P>
He said 25 officers had been convicted of corruption, ranging
from accepting bribes from suspects to stealing petrol from the
police stores.
</P>
<P>
He said the SAPS viewed the involvement of police in corruption
in a serious light.
</P>
<P>
"We will not leave any stone unturned until we root out all the
corrupt officers in the service," he said. 
</P>
