<HEADLINE> S. Africa Makes Final Salary Offer to Public Servants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The South African government
has made a final offer to public servants on a 6 percent increase
of their salary, Public Service and Administration Minister
Geraldine Fraser-Moleketi said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
But the government was willing to negotiate employee benefits
with public service unions, she told reporters in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the 12 public service unions last
month rejected the 6 percent offer. Most of the unions are
demanding a pay rise of 10 percent for the 2000-2001 financial
year.
</P>
<P>
"The 6 percent offer on the salary increase is final, but we
are open to discussion on areas related to benefits,"
Fraser-Moleketi said.
</P>
<P>
She said joint task teams were established to discuss the
restructuring of employee benefits such as leave, medical aid,
pension funds, HIV/AIDS policy and housing.
</P>
<P>
"The current employee benefits are not equitable, affordable
and not accessible by all," she said.
</P>
<P>
Fraser-Moleketi also reiterated that the government was
committed to ending non-statutory salary deductions.
</P>
<P>
"This (non-statutory deductions) adds to pressures for
increased disposable income of public service employees," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The wage negotiations started on May 15, but broke down on June
30 when the unions indicated that they intended to declare a
dispute.
</P>
<P>
Fraser-Moleketi said they were still locked in informal
discussions with the unions.
</P>
<P>
"We are now waiting for the unions to take the dispute
further," Fraser- Moleketi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
