<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Federation of Trade
Unions (ZFTU) has expressed the hope that the new lawmakers will
do their endeavors to legislate for a living wage.
</P>
<P>
ZFTU Secretary General Ephraim Tsvaringe Sunday said in a
statement that workers in the various sectors of Zimbabwe's
economy were grossly underpaid and in most cases were not paid a
living wage.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, it is our sincere hope that new lawmakers,
some of whom are former trade unionists, will make every
endeavour to legislate for a living wage so that the generality of
the Zimbabwean workers comes out of this economic malaise," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the union welcomed last weekend's parliamentary
election results as the people had spoken.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, it was the implementation and fulfillment of
the party manifestos of the two major players in the governance of
the country which the electorate awaited.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabweans had demonstrated their political maturity
and the electoral laws of the country were above board.
</P>
<P>
"Having attained this high degree of democratic governance, it
is therefore imperative that we guard jealously our hard-won
independence, sovereignty, integrity and that foreign powers
should desist from dictating terms to us or interfering with our
internal affairs," he said. 
</P>
