<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexicans Start to Vote in Presidential Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of voting stations
were opened Sunday morning in Mexico for nearly 58 million people
to choose the next president, senators and deputies.
</P>
<P>
In the most prominent election in the history of Mexico, they
will also elect three govonarates for the state of Guanajuato,
Moreleo and the Federal District of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
So far the voting has been carried out calmly, and no violence
has been reported in a country of 974 million people.
</P>
<P>
Voting was under way in the presidential election expected to
be a close contest between former Interior Minister Francisco
Labastida of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI)
and ex-state governor Vicente Fox, of the conservative National
Action Party (PAN). Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of the center-left Party
of the Democratic Revolution (PRD) was seen running a distant
third.
</P>
<P>
This represents the strongest electoral challenge against the
PRI, which has ruled for 71 years, longer than any other party in
the world that is still in power.
</P>
<P>
The Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) took power in 1929,
with opinion polls predicting a neck and neck race between the PRI
's Francisco Labastida and conservative candidate Vicente Fox.
</P>
<P>
Labastida, 57, and Fox, who turned 58 Sunday, are both former
state governors.
</P>
<P>
In the voting, 862 foreign observers and 36,788 locals attended.
</P>
<P>
But many of the international electoral observers following the
balloting have expressed confidence there would be none of the
actual vote-rigging that had allegedly marked past elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
