<HEADLINE> Removal of Mistrust Between U.S., Iran Not Easy: Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Speaker of Iran's reformist Majlis
(parliament) Mehdi Karrubi said here Sunday that it is not easy
to remove the wall of mistrust between Iran and the United States.
</P>
<P>
A lot of effort is required to break the wall of mistrust
between the two countries, said Karrubi at the end of an open
session of the new parliament, which was inaugurated on May 27.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "it is very difficult to draw an optimistic
picture for normalization of Iran-U.S. ties," the Islamic Republic
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The parliament speaker added, however, that Iran has taken a
number of steps to help strengthen understanding between the two
countries, especially since President Mohammad Khatami took office
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The idea of dialogue among civilizations, policy of detente and
exchange of sports and scientific delegations have all been aimed
at helping the American people have a better understanding of the
Iranian nation and the problems created by the U.S. government for
the Iranian nation, Karrubi pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Iran and the U.S. severed diplomatic relations following Iran's
1979 Islamic revolution and the hostage taking of U.S. diplomats by
radical Islamic students in the U.S. embassy in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Ties between the two countries have thawed a little since
moderate President Khatami took office.
</P>
<P>
In March, Washington declared the lifting of a ban on three
major Iranian non-oil exports -- of pistachio, carpets and caviar -
-
as a goodwill gesture to Iranian reformers who won an overwhelming
victory in the sixth parliament election in February.
</P>
<P>
But the Clinton administration still keeps the major part of
economic sanctions and sticks to its accusations that Iran supports
international terrorism, attempts to make mass-destructive weapons
and opposes the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Conservative hardliners in Iran also strongly opposes the
normalization of relations with the U.S., maintaining that
Washington, the main foe of Iran,attempts to stir up social and
political unrest in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
