<HEADLINE> Cairo, Tehran Hold Talks on Normalization of Relations: Egyptian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said on Sunday Cairo and Tehran have held talks on the
normalization of relations severed after Egypt signed a peace
agreement with Israel in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon return following visits to Poland,
Malaysia and Singapore, Moussa said the Egyptian-Iranian talks were
held "at high level" and bilateral relations "are making progress."
But he did not mention when and where the talks were held.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said he "discussed ways of giving boost to the relations"
with his Iranian counterpart Kamal Kharazi on the sidelines of a
foreign ministers meeting of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference in Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
On June 21, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Iranian
President Mohammad Khatami held a telephone conversation in the
first direct contact between leaders of the two countries in more
than two decades.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak informed Khatami of Iran's accession to the Group-15
during its summit in Cairo on June 19-20.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian and Iranian officials often discuss regional issues on
occasions of multilateral meetings in recent years. The two
countries also seek means to promote economic and trade
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has said it is ready to re-establish full diplomatic
relations as soon as Iran changed the name of Khaled al-Islambouli
Street in Tehran, which was named after the man who assassinated
Egyptian President Anwar Sadat in 1980.  
</P>
