<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Ready For Talks With India: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Yes, we can hold talks as per the agreed agenda. We have the
two-plus-six agenda of 1997 and the Lahore Declaration. Pakistan
is not in violation of any of these," Qazi, who is on a three-day
visit to the northeastern Indian city of Calcutta, was quoted as
saying by the Press Trust of India (PTI).
</P>
<P>
According to the two-plus-six agenda, which was worked out in
Islamabad in June 1997 by the two sides and had identified eight
outstanding bilateral issues between the two south Asian neighbors,
foreign secretaries of both countries will discuss peace and
security including confidence building measures that would deal
with the nuclear issue, the arms race and the Kashmir question,
Qazi noted.
</P>
<P>
Other issues listed in the agenda included terrorism and drug
trafficking and economic and business cooperation between the two
sides, said the PTI.
</P>
<P>
The agenda was later reiterated in the Lahore Declaration
following a summit meeting between Indian Prime Minister Vajpayee
and the then Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in February
1998.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan was ready to hold talks strictly according to the June
1997 agreement and the February 1998 Lahore Declaration, said Qazi.
</P>
<P>
In his address in Calcutta, Qazi also urged India to hold
bilateral discussions on Kashmir with Pakistan, said the PTI.
</P>
<P>
"You need to adopt a pragmatic approach and an open mind. You
have already lost the battle of hearts and minds in Kashmir," Qazi
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani envoy also expressed his country's keenness to
exchange information with India on the two neighbors' nuclear
command and control systems.
</P>
<P>
"We need to know each other's nuclear philosophy and command
and control systems," he said, adding that India and Pakistan
should keep each other informed in this regard just as what Russia
and the United States have done. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
