<HEADLINE> Abu Sayyaf Abducts German Journalist in Jolo) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MANILA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Muslim extremist group Abu
Sayyaf kidnapped a German journalist in Jolo on Sunday who tried
to get in touch with its 20 mostly foreign hostages, according to
a local TV report.
</P>
<P>
Andreas Lorenz, who works for a German weekly news magazine,
was seized by the Abu Sayyaf rebels on his way to their lair in
the jungles of Jolo island in the southern Philippines, said the
report of the ABS-CBN news channel.
</P>
<P>
The rebels took Lorenz away from a car he was riding in, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Lorenz had talked to two contacts on how to get in touch with
the hostages held by the Abu Sayyaf, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The rebel group, which released one Malaysian on June 2, is
still holding eight Malaysians, three Germans, two French, two
Finns, two South Africans, two Filipinos and one Lebanese, who
were abducted from the Malaysian resort of Sipadan and brought to
Jolo on April 23.
</P>
<P>
On June 2, Abu Sayyaf rebels held captive 10 Western
journalists covering the hostage crisis in Jolo, and released them
later in the day after they were paid a ransom of one million
pesos (about 25,000 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
