<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are the economic briefs
in the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey is badly in need of natural gas as the gas
consumption is sharply on the rise, reported Turkish daily News on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
General Manager of the state-owned Turkish Pipeline Company
(BOTAS) Gokhan Yardim said at a meeting in Izmir in southwest
Turkey that the country's natural gas consumption rises by 19
percent annually, the highest growth rate in the world.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the economic growth, industrialization, increase
in population and fast urbanization to the roaring energy
consumption, especially natural gas.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is expected to consume 15 billion cubic meters of natural
gas in 2000 and 55 billion in 2010.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has signed natural gas agreements with Russia,
Turkmenistan and Iran, and liquid natural gas agreements with
Algeria and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's production, domestic sales and exports of
television sets rose by 35 percent in the runup period to the Euro
2000 Soccer Championship and the Olympic Games in Sydney,
Australia, reported the Anatolia News Agency on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Maral Oztekin, president of the Association of Electronic Goods
Manufacturers, said that the output of TV sets in the first five
months of 2000 increased to 3.56 million from 2.64 million in the
same period of 1999. Meanwhile, big-screen TV set sales rose from
403,000 to 660,000.
</P>
<P>
"We expected a 15 percent increase in TV sales, but Euro 2000
and Sydney Olympics have doubled the sales," he said.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Turkish Tourism Investors Association (TYD) and
the Greek Tourism Entrepreneurs Association (AGTE) decided to work
together in the tourism sector, reported the Anatolia News Agency
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The TYD and AGTE representatives met in Bodrum, west Turkey, on
Saturday night and decided to turn the Aegean to a "sea of peace"
and explore the Aegean tourism market. They also agreed on
exchanges of tourism personnel.
</P>
<P>
There will be two tourism fairs in Salonica, Greece, in fall and
in Istanbul in February, 2001. Both associations will be
represented at the fairs.
</P>
<P>
A joint committee will meet in Istanbul in July and in Athens in
August.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The gross domestic product (GDP) of Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) states in 1999 reached 266.5 billion U.S.
dollars against 260.8 billion dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Industrial Investment Agency's release attributed the
upsurge to the upward oil price last year and the burgeoning growth
rates in Europe and Asia which led to a rise in total earnings of
GCC members from 42 billion dollars in l998 to over 70 billion
dollars in l999.
</P>
<P>
The improving economic performance in GCC states brought about
GDP growth from 1.03 percent in l998 to 2.21 percent in 1999, the
release said.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the OPEC members' compliance with the March, l999,
Crude Reduction Agreement, the GCC states had more oil revenues
which stepped up their economic growth, according to the release.
The GCC states are the biggest oil producers in OPEC.
</P>
<P>
The United Arab Emirates (UAE) achieved the highest growth rates
among GCC countries to 4.0 percent followed by Oman 3.7 percent,
Bahrain 3.2 percent, Saudi Arabia 1.8 percent, Qatar 1.3 percent
and Kuwait 0.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
