<HEADLINE> (Updated) Uganda, Rwanda Vow to Improve Bilateral Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
and his Rwandan counterpart Paul Kagame agreed on Sunday to
explore ways to improve relations between the two countries after
their troops repeatedly clashed in the northern Congolese city of
Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
According to the joint communique issued at the end of the
talks in Entebbe, 40 kilometers south of the Ugandan capital
Kampala, the two leaders reiterated their strong commitment to the
Lusaka Cease-fire Agreement and resolved to work together for its
full and rapid implementation.
</P>
<P>
"They also reaffirmed their commitment to the demilitarization
of the northeast Congolese city of Kisangani, and called on other
parties to the Cease-fire Agreement to reciprocate and not take
advantage of Rwanda and Uganda's withdrawal from Kisangani," said
the communique.
</P>
<P>
"The two Heads of State called upon the United Nations to fully
deploy U. N. observers in Congo to support the cease-fire
agreement," it said.
</P>
<P>
The talks on the bilateral and regional issues started soon
after Kagame arrived at the Entebbe International Airport Saturday
afternoon and continued on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
The forces of the two former allies withdrew from Kisangani
after they shelled each other in early June in the third largest
city of DRC, killing over 100 soldiers and more than 300
civilians.
</P>
<P>
They have clashed for the control of the diamond trade center
for three times since last August.
</P>
<P>
The last summit between the two leaders took place in Mwanza,
Tanzania, after the second clash in early May.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda sent troops to back different rebel groups
fighting against the DRC President Laurent Kabila supported by
armies from Angola, Namibia and Zimbabwe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
