<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Personal Financial Records Database Operational in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- This metropolis in east China has
started the operation of a database on the personal financial
records of 1.1 million local residents.
</P>
<P>
This is the first database of its kind in the whole country.
The database, run by the Shanghai Credit Information Service Co.
Ltd, collects all the information on a resident's lending and
borrowing records and bank accounts in all the financial
institutions, serving as a reference for banks and social
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Banks will dial a number into the database before making a
decision on whether or not to grant loans to an applicant. Bank
staff will be able to get the needed information on the particular
person in five seconds.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the database will improve credit card business
and reduce the loan risks and operational costs of banks and
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Such database have long been in existence in developed
countries, and for 17 years in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
With the approval of the People's Bank of China, Shanghai
started the database construction in June last year.
</P>
<P>
Other Chinese cities are expected to get approval for similar
databases, it was learned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
