<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reaches World's Advanced Level in Remote Sensing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- China's remote sensing technology,
which is widely used in the domestic grain output assessment,
resource exploration and disaster monitoring, has reached the
world's advanced level, said an expert from the Chinese Academy of
Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
Though China has a more complicated situation of crop
cultivation, the accuracy of image and data processing of the
grain output assessment in China is on a par with that in the
United States and European countries, said Nie Yueping, a
researcher from the Institute of Remote Sensing Application under
the CAS.
</P>
<P>
He said that the institute used data from meteorological
satellites to monitor the growth of winter wheat in 11 provinces
and municipalities in north China during the 1986-1990 period, and
provided important reference for the government's grain purchase
plan in summer.
</P>
<P>
During the 1991-1995 period, the institute built an information
system to monitor and estimate the output of the three major kinds
of crops in China -- wheat, corn and paddy rise -- which account
for more than 85 percent of the country's total grain output.
</P>
<P>
The institute is now able to provide services for monitoring
and estimating the growth and output of crops all over the country.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at the institute also use satellite remote sensing
techniques to monitor the expansion of urban areas and the illegal
use of farmland for construction. In addition, remote sensing
plays an important role in the monitoring and forecasting of
natural disasters such as floods and drought.
</P>
<P>
"We have even used the technology to do some things which we
had never expected to do," said Nie. "For example, we used it to
help discover buried cultural relics."
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the institute provided remote sensing pictures
of an ancient tomb in suburban Beijing to archeologists, who
decided that there were other tombs of the same size near the
original one.
</P>
<P>
Nie said that the next goal for the institute is to do global
grain output assessment. With an estimation of grain output
worldwide, China will be able to adjust the domestic grain growth
and output accordingly, and thus play a better role in global
economic integration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
