<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects Foreign Criticism of Verdicts on Jews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Sunday strongly rejected
Western criticism of its sentencing 10 Iranian Jews on charges of
spying for Israel as "foreign intervention."
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi said Iran would not
accept any interventionist attitudes aimed at influencing its
judicial process.
</P>
<P>
"The courts of the Islamic Republic of Iran investigated the
case and issued verdicts independently," Asefi said, "political
stands of no country would have any impact on the judicial process
of the courts."
</P>
<P>
Iran's revolutionary court on Saturday sentenced 10 out of 13
Jews, and two Muslims accused of spying to terms ranging from four
to 13 years in prison. The other three Jews were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
The 13 Jews were arrested more than one year ago in Shiraz,
capital of Fars Province, the center of Iran's Jewish community of
about 25,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The accused have been treated kindly and they also have the
right to appeal, the spokesman said, quoted by the official IRNA
news agency.
</P>
<P>
The arrest and trial of the Jews sparked protests from Israel
and Western countries who demanded their release. Iran insisted
that the case has nothing to do with religious beliefs and no
foreign country should interfere in its domestic affairs.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., France and a number of EU countries have condemned the
verdicts.
</P>
<P>
Asefi called on the Western governments to observe the
principles of international law and refrain from interfering in the
domestic affairs of other states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
