<HEADLINE> Injured Iranians Released from Hospital in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A total of 39 Iranians out of 43
accident-survived passengers were released after treatment in
hospital of Erzurum, east Turkey, on Sunday, reported the Anatolia
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
A traffic accident took place in Erzurum province Saturday night
when a long-distance Iranian passenger bus, coming from Tehran to
Istanbul, was turning over from an overpass in Yenisehir
intersection. All the 43 occupants were injured.
</P>
<P>
The other four Iranians, including the bus driver, still remain
in the hospital for further treatment.
</P>
<P>
Lutfullah Zakeri, Iranian Chief Consul in Erzurum, thanked
Erzurum Governor Derya Kadioglu, police officials and hospital
staff for the timely rescue and medical treatment of the Iranian
passengers.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is notorious for frequent traffic accidents. Over the
last two decades, the number of people who died in traffic
accidents has totalled 163,000, and more than one million injured.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, President Ahmet Necdet Sezer underlined the need to
enact a traffic law to lessen traffic accidents and do away with
fatal tragedies.
</P>
<P>
A traffic law will be beneficial to the entire society, said the
president while receiving Boray Uras, who lost his daughter in a
traffic accident in Istanbul earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Uras traveled from Istanbul to Ankara on foot to draw public
attention to Turkey's traffic problem and rally support for passing
a traffic law. 
</P>
