<HEADLINE> No Date Set For Three-Way Summit: Barak EDS-Retransmitting with corrections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- No date has been set for a three-
way summit in Washington to discuss the Middle East peace process,
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Briefing his cabinet about the ongoing Israeli-Palestinian
final-status talks and the proposed three-way summit between
himself, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and U.S. President Bill
Clinton, Barak said Clinton has not made up his mind to call the
summit in the near future.
</P>
<P>
"Only President Clinton has the right to decide on when to hold
this summit, but the president decided to postpone to make such a
decision and therefore there will be no three-way summit for the
near future," Barak said.
</P>
<P>
Barak strongly supported the idea of convening this summit,
saying it is time for both Israeli and Palestinian leaders to make
decisions on key issues discussed in the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
But the idea was opposed by Arafat. He refused to attend the
summit before gaps between the Palestinians and Israel are narrowed
on all key issues including Jerusalem, borders, refugees, and
Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
Arafat instead urged Clinton to organize another round of
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations to narrow the gaps before calling
for a summit.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Israeli Attorney General Elyakim
Rubinstein stuck to his position that the United Nations Security
Council Resolutions 242 and 338 did not apply to Israeli-
Palestinian negotiations to solve the border issues, saying the
resolutions were passed more than 25 years ago before the
establishment of the Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
His similar remarks Thursday drew rebuff from the Palestinians
and the United States, who said the two U.N. resolutions calling
for Israel to withdraw from occupied territories and talks to start
for "establishing a just and durable peace," are the basis for
resolving the Middle East conflict.
</P>
<P>
In an official statement issued Friday in the West Bank city of
Ramallah, Arafat sharply denounced this Israeli position, which he
said is very dangerous and "Israel is making an effort to thwart
the whole peace process."
</P>
<P>
Also rejecting Rubinstein's position, the United states said
Saturday that the resolutions do apply to Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Justice Minister Yossi Beilin said on Sunday that
Rubinstein's position is wrong and his remarks did not represent
the government's stance on this issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
