<HEADLINE> Impersonators Escape with Weapons From Army Camp in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A group of men posing as army
personnel escaped with a substantial amount of weapons from an
army camp in northern Malaysia, Defense Minister Najib Tun Razak
said.
</P>
<P>
In the incident early Sunday morning, 15 impersonators dressed
in Malaysian army camouflage uniforms entered the 304 territorial
army camp at Pengkalan Hulu in the northern state of Perak, he
said at the Subang air force base near here.
</P>
<P>
"All 15 of them came and fled in three green Pajero vehicles
bearing military plates," he told reporters after receiving
Singapore Defense Minister Tony Tan.
</P>
<P>
M16 and Steyr rifles were among the more than 90 weapons carted
away.
</P>
<P>
He said the men told the sentries that they were there to make
a surprise check.
</P>
<P>
The guards tried to verify the matter with higher authorities,
but the group "asserted authority with their ranks" and demanded
to be taken to the armory.
</P>
<P>
Najib said the police and the army were conducting a major
operation in areas near the borders to track down the suspects,
adding the incident was professionally planned and unprecedented
in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
