<HEADLINE> Malaysian Deputy PM Tells Reason for Military Weapons Theft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Poor security check and weapon
control system allowed impersonators to cart away an assortment of
weaponry from an army camp in Malaysia's northern state of Perak
early Sunday, Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said.
</P>
<P>
The incident showed that procedures relating to security
maintenance at key installations such as weapons depot were
ignored, Abdullah also Home Minister, said in the northern state
of Pulau Pinang, Bernama news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A group of 15 impersonators dressed in Malaysian army
camouflage uniforms complete with ranks and berets entered the 304
Territorial Army camp at Pengkalan Hulu in Perak and carted away
more than 90 weapons including M16 and rifles, as officially
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said when security consideration was not put first,
incidents like the one in Pengkalan Hulu Sunday and the abduction
in Sipadan Island, off Sabah, East Malaysia, last April were bound
to happen.
</P>
<P>
Armed gunmen kidnapped 21 people, comprising Malaysians and
other foreign nationals, from Sipadan and are still holding 20 of
them in southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"We should learn from these incidents," Abdullah was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He warned the prevailing peace had lulled Malaysians into
complacency, assuming that nothing could breach the security.
</P>
</TEXT>
