<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Conference on Integrated Medicine Held in Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- International Conference on
Integrated Medicine was held here Sunday, with about 400 delegates
from over ten countries sharing their experiences in the
development of traditional medicine and discussing the prospects
for the integrated medicine.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the opening ceremony of the two-day conference,
Chinese Health Minister Zhang Wenkang said as part of human
civilization, traditional medicine contribute to the health of
peoples in many countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government, fully recognizing the
historical contribution, scientific and practical value of
traditional Chinese medicine, views it as a treasure of the
Chinese civilization and strives to modernize it.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy to see that more and more people in the world are
paying attention to traditional medicine," he said, adding that
the Chinese government wishes to do its best to promote exchange
and cooperation between countries and further promote the
development of traditional medicine.
</P>
<P>
Of traditional and modern medicines, he said, "We also
encourages the integration of the two medicines. While retaining
their own theoretical systems and methodologies, they can also
integrate and infiltrate into each other, learn from each other to
improve the clinical efficacy and theoretical level," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
World Health Organization (WHO) representative to Thailand E.B.
Doberstyn said WHO has long recognized that there is an extremely
rich history of traditional health systems, practices and remedies
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
WHO will support member countries to integrate traditional
medicines into their national health and drug policies, promote
the proper use of traditional medicines, improve research
methodologies to study efficacy, quality, safety and application
of traditional medicines and collect and disseminate up-to-date
information on traditional medicines, he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that international trade in herbal medicines has been
increasing, he said that there is an urgent need to redefine
regulations governing the use of herbal medicines and change the
regulations when necessary to assure quality, safety and
standardization of the remedies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
