<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Orders PNA Officials to Stay Put: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Preparing for a unilateral
statehood declaration, Palestinian National Authority Chairman
Yasser Arafat issued an order late last week banning departures of
top PNA officials as of next month, the Israeli daily Ha'aretz
reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Starting August 3, top PNA officials will not be allowed to
leave PNA territories unless Arafat himself personally approves
special departure requests, the paper reported, citing a
Palestinian Liberation Organization (PLO) member.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's no-travel order attests to stepped-up preparations in
the PNA, as the September 13 target date nears. Palestinian leaders
have vowed that they will declared the conclusion of the interim
phase on that date.
</P>
<P>
Arafat wants his top officials to stay close by in anticipation
of violent clashes and possibly punitive Israeli measures following
a unilateral statehood declaration.
</P>
<P>
About 100 members of the PLO's Central Council are meeting in
the Gaza Strip Sunday and Monday to discuss a series of final-
status issues, among them the date for the statehood declaration.
</P>
<P>
In another development, both the Palestinians and the Untied
States have rebuffed an Israeli interpretation that U.N.
resolutions do not require Israeli withdrawal from the occupied
territories.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, Israeli Attorney General Elyakim Rubinstein
argued that U.N. resolutions 242 and 338 do not apply to Israeli-
PNA negotiations, since they were passed more than 25 years before
the establishment of the Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
Arafat sharply denounced "this dangerous Israeli position"
Friday evening. In an official statement he charged that Israel is
showing contempt for international law and U.N. decisions.
</P>
<P>
By distancing itself from the U.N. resolutions "Israel is making
an effort to thwart the whole peace process," Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the PNA leadership sent urgent letters to the United
Nations and various countries, calling on them to force Israel to
comply with binding international decisions.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. also rejected Rubinstein's position, and reiterated
that the U.N. resolutions applies to negotiations between Israel
and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Angered by the stagnant peace negotiations and the extremely dim
prospects of reaching a comprehensive and permanent peace before
the September 13 deadline, Arafat has reiterated his determination
to declare statehood in September, even without a deal with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli side retaliated by stepping up threats over a
unilateral declaration of Palestinian statehood. Israeli Prime
Minister called on the U.S. to hold a three-way summit between him,
Arafat and U.S. President Bill Clinton to make crucial decisions.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has yet to announce whether there will be a summit under
the present situation where the two sides remain far apart on most
of the major issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
