<DOCNO> XIE20000702.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. FAO Chief Concludes Visit to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) Director-General Jacques Diouf
concluded his two-day visit to Iraq and left the country on Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
It was a low-profile departure with no press conference or
statements, a U.N. source told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The FAO chief arrived here Friday after two FAO staff were
killed in its Baghdad office by a gunman Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Diouf held talks with Iraqi Vice President
Taha Yassin Ramadan, Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz, Agriculture
Minister Abdul Ellan Hameed and Irrigation Minister Mahmoud Diyab
Al-Ahmad.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi leadership highly appreciated the efforts exerted by
the FAO to alleviate the plight of the Iraqi people, who have been
under sanctions ever since Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the FAO chief promised that his organization will
continue to make efforts to better implement the U.N. oil-for-food
program.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz on
Saturday, Diouf said that Iraq is still a full member of the FAO,
so his organization should work hard to ensure Iraqi's humanitarian
needs.
</P>
<P>
The FAO office in Iraq is mainly in charge of the implementation
of the U.N. humanitarian deal, which allows Iraq to export a
limited amount of crude to finance imports of food, medicine and
essential parts for its oil and electricity sectors.
</P>
<P>
A gunman, identified as 38-year-old Fuad Haidar, burst into the
FAO office building in central Baghdad early Wednesday morning,
shot and killed two FAO staffers and wounded several others.
</P>
<P>
After a two-hour confrontation with the security forces, the
killer surrendered and is now under custody in the Jadria Police
Bureau in central Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Amir Khalil, the FAO representative in Baghdad, said that the
Iraqi government has promised to provide "maximum security" for the
400 U.N.staff in Iraq, and security has been reinforced outside U.
N. offices in Baghdad since the tragic incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
