<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 11 Indonesian Ship Wreckage Survivors Found: Antara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 11 people, consisted of men, women and children, were found
floating in the waters aboard Minahasa IX ship. Most of them wore
life vests and others held on to debris, said Setia Rahardjo, head
of the government's search and rescue agency.
</P>
<P>
Minahasa IX, heading to Tobelo (North Maluku) from Manado (
North Sulawesi), found the 11 people in the waters close to the
Karakelong island, about 192 kilometers northeast of Manado on
Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
The survivors had confirmed that the heavily overcrowded vessel
had sunk after taking in water in rough seas and strong winds.
</P>
<P>
The survivors were dehydrated, sunburned and weakened by hunger,
Rahardjo said, adding that rescuers had so far found no evidence
of the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers said a search of the area where the survivors were
found was still going on, but the chance of more survivors seemed
slim.
</P>
<P>
The passenger ship, Cahaya Bahari, left Tobelo on Halmahera in
North Maluku province on Wednesday en route to Manado. Radio
contact with the vessel was lost after its captain M.M. Paparaga
radioed an "SOS" advising that the ship was taking water in fast
during a violent storm at noon on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
There is conflicting data about the total passengers on board
as the Cahaya Bahari was licensed to carry only 270 people. The
National Search and Rescue Agency claimed that at least 492
passengers, refugees from Maluku and crew may have been aboard.
</P>
</TEXT>
