<DOCNO> XIE20000702.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Transfer 1,000 SLA Refugees to Other Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Israel is considering transferring
about 1,000 former Israeli-allied South Lebanon Army (SLA)
militiamen and their family members to other countries, a Interior
Ministry official disclosed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of such ex-SLA militiamen wanting to move abroad
will be flown to Germany next week if all bureaucratic procedures
are smooth as expected, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Israel is also conducting intensive talks with other countries,
mostly in North and South America, to persuade them to absorb some
SLA refugees.
</P>
<P>
The work will be coordinated by Shin Bet (Israel's General
Security Service) assistance teams with the refugees, the official
added.
</P>
<P>
Some 6,000 SLA militiamen and their family members have been
taking shelter in Israel since May after their army collapsed under
pressure of Lebanese resistance guerrillas, and Israel withdrew
from the so-called security zone in south Lebanon later.
</P>
<P>
About 3,000 SLA militiamen had been fighting along with Israeli
occupying troops against Lebanese resistance groups since the
security zone was set up by Israel in 1985 with a self-claimed aim
to protect its northern border.
</P>
<P>
Most high-ranking SLA officers, together with their families,
fled to Israel for fear of being captured by Lebanese authorities
to face possible death sentences for collaborating with the enemy.
</P>
<P>
However, their life in Israel is not easy as they could only
receive a monthly allowance of between 2,400-3,400 shekels (about
588-833 U.S. dollars), whereas the average earning for Israelis is
6,000 shekels (1,471 dollars). They also have difficulties in
finding housing and jobs in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Around 300 former SLA militiamen and families had crossed back
into Lebanon. It is estimated that once the situation in south
Lebanon stabilizes, more refugees will decide to return to their
homes.
</P>
<P>
Those choosing to return will receive one-off compensation from
Israeli government in light of their service years in the army. For
example, a regular soldier who served 20 years will receive nearly
30,000 dollars, according to a brochure distributed by the
government.
</P>
<P>
However, once they return to Lebanon they will stand trial for
their roles as traitors during the 22 years of Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks, Lebanese military court tried 10 batches
of SLA collaborators. Most of them received sentences ranging from
one-year to 15-year imprisonment, while three SLA soldiers were
condemned to death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
