<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore May Have Water Supply From Indonesia in 5 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Water could be piped from
Indonesia to Singapore as early as 2005 if a proposed 1.5 billion
U.S. dollars-deal can be finalized this week, local English
newspaper The Sunday Times reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The paper also said that Singapore will have a new source in
Riau Province, Indonesia, in five years if the massive engineering
project involving overland channels and undersea pipelines gets
off the ground.
</P>
<P>
Government-owned Riau State Holdings President/Director
Arsyadjuliandi Rachman was quoted as saying that representatives
from the Riau provincial government will head for Singapore this
week to finalize the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The project, estimated to cost at least 1.5 billion U.S.
dollars and expected to supply water to Singapore for "a long,
long term," will harness a water catchment area of some 51,000
square kilometers, 80 times the size of Singapore, in Indonesia's
Riau province and the water will be channeled through two undersea
pipelines -- a 250 kilometers line from Riau's Sungai Kampar river
to Bintan, Indonesia, and another 200 kilometers line from Bintan
to Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The project is said to involve Indonesia-listed Upton Synergy
Indonesia (USI), the Riau government-owned Riau State Holdings and
Singapore Technologies as well as international partners.
</P>
<P>
The governments of Singapore and Indonesia entered into
agreement in 1991 for the development of water resources in
Indonesia and the supply of water to Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The 1991 agreement, valid for 100 years, allows Singapore to
purchase up to 4.5 billion liters of water a day from Indonesia's
Riau province.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of Singapore buying water from Indonesia also
cropped up in talks between Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong
and Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid in January when Goh
visited Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Singapore has depended on Malaysia for its water supply. Johor,
the southern most state of Malaysia, supplies 214 million liters
of raw water a day to Singapore and buys back 35 million liters of
treated water from Singapore's water treatment plant in Johor.
</P>
<P>
The two pacts on water supply Singapore signed with Johor in
1961 and 1962 will expire in 2011 and 2061, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
