<HEADLINE> Military Plane Crashes in Southwestern Philippines EDS-Updates with more details and correction in location </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A nine-seater Nomad plane of the
Philippine Air Force crashed near Calusa Island in the
southwestern province of Palawan Sunday morning, killing at least
two persons aboard, according to a TV report.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of the two victims, Armed Forces Western Command
commander Maj. Gen. Santiago Madrid and the co-pilot, were found
and one survivor, identified as Bruce Walker, was rescued by Local
fishermen near the crash site, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which took off in Palawan's Cagayancillo town past
10 a.m., probably developed an engine trouble, said the report of
the ABS-CBN news channel.
</P>
<P>
The survivor said two engines of the plane gave out before it
tried to descend, the report said, adding that the real cause of
the crash was not yet known.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Palawan governor Salvador Socrates was
among the passengers of the ill-fated plane. but it did not say
how many people were on board. The Navy has dispatched three ships
to help search for other possible survivors.
</P>
<P>
The light transport plane was said to be flying on a civic
mission to Puerto Princesa, capital of Palawan, when it crashed.
</P>
</TEXT>
