<HEADLINE> Former Tanzanian President Urges Collective Efforts Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Former Tanzanian President
Ali Hassan Mwinyi has called for greater collective efforts to
sensitize and mobilize the people on the control of AIDS, as its
infection rate continues escalating in this east African country.
</P>
<P>
The official Sunday News quoted the former president as saying
here on Saturday that escalating rate of AIDS pandemic in
Tanzania reflects lack of seriousness among the people on
awareness programs.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after leading a fund raising charity walk for the
establishment of an AIDS awareness Youth Radio project, Mwinyi
called for more effective means of communications to mobilize and
sensitize the public.
</P>
<P>
Mwinyi, chairman of the national advisory board on HIV/AIDS,
said despite the efforts by the government, donor agencies and
individuals to check further spread of the killer disease,
thousands of lives continue to perish in the country.
</P>
<P>
He also called on people, particularly young people to change
their life style and sexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
A recent World Bank report predicted Tanzania's gross domestic
product will decline by between 15 and 25 percent by 2015 if AIDS
continues to spread at the current rate.
</P>
<P>
Researchers estimate about 20 percent of Tanzania's 33.3
million people are HIV-positive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
