<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No End to Conflict with Israel in Framework Accord: Qurei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian side will refuse
to sign a framework agreement that declares an end to the conflict
with Israel, a senior Palestinian official has said.
</P>
<P>
"We will only declare an end to the conflict when Israel has
implement the final peace deal," including an agreement on
Jerusalem and refugees, Palestinian chief negotiator Ahmed Qurei,
also known as Abu Ala, was quoted by Israeli daily the Jerusalem
Post as saying on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Qurei said that the Palestinians have learned a lesson from
the "bad experiences with the interim agreement," which Israel
still has not fully implemented, although an agreement on its
implementation was signed at Sharm el Sheikh, Egypt, last
September.
</P>
<P>
The Sharm el Sheikh peace deal asks the two sides to reach a
framework agreement in February before striking a final peace deal
in September, while setting out specific regulations stipulating
Israel's troop redeployment in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, the
release of Palestinians from Israeli jails and opening of safe
passages linking the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has proposed that the
framework agreement for a final peace deal must state the Israeli-
Palestinian conflict is over. Barak also said he wants to keep the
important key final-status issues including Jerusalem, refugees,
border, Jewish settlements for the leaders to decide at a three-way
summit between himself, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and U.S.
President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians are requesting the U.S. to organize another
round of talks soon before calling for a summit.
</P>
<P>
Qurei said negotiations are meaningless unless Barak gives his
negotiators a mandate to narrow the gaps, warning that an early
summit would end in failure and lead to frustration on the
Palestinian streets.
</P>
<P>
"There can be no negotiations without authorization by the
leaders," he said. "If the Israeli negotiators have no mandate to
take decisions, we should leave things up to the summit or to
circumstances," he added, implying that the Palestinian people may
opt for violence if no satisfactory agreement can be reached.
</P>
<P>
"Israel must recognize that East Jerusalem is part of the
territories occupied in 1967, then we will discuss the Israeli
needs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qurei also stressed that the United Nations Security Council
Resolutions 242 and 338 must be the basis of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Qurei, who heads the Palestinian delegation to the final-status
talks with Israeli Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami, said
that the only breakthrough was in discussions over the Jordan
Valley, but that was not written down for the record.
</P>
<P>
On the Jewish settlements, one of the key final-status issues,
Qurei said that "the settlers can stay if they apply for residency
or citizenship of the Palestinian state and the Palestinian side
will review each application, but only on an individual basis, not
as groups or communities." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
