<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Israeli newspapers on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Lebanon is violating U.N. Resolution 425 by failing to send
troops to the border in order to take control of the south, Israel
complained to United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Since Israel withdrew from the zone on May 24, Lebanon has
accused Israel of not complying fully with resolution 425. The UN's
approval of the withdrawal on June 16 was held up over Lebanese
complaints that IDF troops were still located in Lebanese territory
in some places.
</P>
<P>
Stone-throwing incidents along the border with Lebanon continued
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli senior rabbis aligned with the religious Zionist
movement want to see an end to the presence of female solider in
elite combat units of the Israel Defense Forces.
</P>
<P>
The rabbis are currently preparing for a public battle on the
matter and believe that the development of combat units for women
will cause serious harm to religious soldiers, perhaps even
bringing their future service in combat units into doubt.
</P>
<P>
Chief of Staff Shaul Mofaz decided 18 months ago to extend
combat roles for women serving in the IDF, a precedent-setting
decision of which Mofaz was very proud.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- As of late Saturday night, no progress had been made toward
solving the Israeli doctors' strike. Doctors will wage a full-scale
strike Sunday, and hospitals around the country will operate on a
Shabbat schedule.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Prime Minister Ehud Barak deferred a recommendation
made by mediators in favor of establishing a public commission to
examine the health system.
</P>
<P>
Barak informed the mediators that such a commission should not
be formed before the Israel Medical Association and the Finance
Ministry resolve all other disputed issues, such as the amount of
wage increments.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- The Palestinian Liberation Organization's Central Committee
will convene in Gaza Sunday to discuss preparations for a
Palestinian state that officials said they were determined to
declare later this year -- with or without a peace treaty with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Legislative Council Speaker Ahmed Qurei, who heads
the Palestinian team to the final-status talks, predicted there
would be a decision to declare statehood this year.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat intends to
declare the state within all the territories captured in the 1967
Six-Day War, with east Jerusalem as its capital, but he does not
intend to extend his authority over territory not yet under his
control, a Palestinian security officer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
