<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 40 Injured in Police-Workers Clash in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 2 (Xinhua) -- About 40 people were injured
during the four-day police-labor confrontation triggered by the
attempt of the striking laborers to block the strategic Indo-Nepal
border connecting with Jogbani of Bihar state of India, police
sources told the press Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The injured included 24 policemen and more than 10 workers, the
source said.
</P>
<P>
"Police used force after the laborers threw brickbats at us,"
said Superintendent Police Kalyan Timalsina.
</P>
<P>
Police was compelled to fire rubber bullets, tear gas, gas
grenade and blank fire to disperse the agitated workers to get the
situation under control, he said.
</P>
<P>
The workers smashed six vehicles, including some government
vehicles, during the confrontations. Police had detained three
people in connection with the vandalism.
</P>
<P>
On May 29, the employees of Biratnagar Jute Mill in Morang
district bordering India resorted to agitation with 16-point
demands protesting against the mill lease-holder Nirmal Vyas'
decision to run the factory in accordance with the Labor Act,
which would curtail some of their facilities, including welfares.
</P>
<P>
When their demands were not fulfilled, the employees closed the
border with 50 trucks lining at the Nepali side of the border,
leading to the paralyze of the transportation on Biratnagar-
Jogbani route and disrupting daily border business.
</P>
<P>
As the workers have threatened to continue the agitation if
their demands are not met, the opposition parties are pressing the
government to help solve the labor dispute as soon as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
