<HEADLINE> Traffic Police Shortage Worsens Traffic Jam in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Insufficient number of traffic police
and inadequate training are making the poor traffic situation in
Dhaka city even worse, The Daily Star newspaper reported here
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Only 1,400 policemen of Dhaka's traffic department are engaged
in maintaining traffic in the capital where more than 300,000
registered motor vehicles and 80,000 licensed rickshaws are plying,
a traffic department official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Besides, over 400,000 illegal rickshaws and carts and a large
number of unlicensed motor vehicles have made the city's traffic
situation precarious with frequent jams on important points, added
the official.
</P>
<P>
Taking advantage of shortage of police force, the unfit and
unlicensed vehicles, illegally parked vehicles and vehicles
without required documents are escaping the punishment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about 70 percent of the traffic force gains no
training on maintaining traffic, the official admitted.
</P>
<P>
Inadequate training is not only resulting in poor service from
traffic policemen but also causing injury to some of them while
discharging duties.
</P>
<P>
The traffic department arranges 10 to 15 days' training on
primary lessons of traffic control for the new recruits at the
department, but this is not at all sufficient, another official
said.
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes they give wrong signals or do not understand what to
do," he said, pointing out the lack of training. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
