<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Urges West to Relax Technology Transfer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has urged the
Western countries to relax terms of technology transfer to least
developed countries to enable the latter to address development
and environmental needs, local newspapers reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Closing an international environmental conference for
sustainable development in Africa here on Friday, Tanzanian
Minister for Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation Jakaya
Kikwete said that lack of appropriate technologies, including new
environmentally friendly technology, was undermining Africa's
resolve to bring drastic economic prospect to its people.
</P>
<P>
"It is disappointing to note that there has not been any real
progress in the technology transfer despite the fact that it was
agreed in the famous Agenda 21 during the UN environmental meeting
in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil in 1992," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Even though technology transfer is included in the Agenda 21
and the Convention on Biological Diversity, these principles can
not be implemented fully due to a stance taken by developed
countries of invoking the protection of intellectual property
rights," he stressed. "This effectively renders technology
transfer on grant and concessional terms by and large inoperable."
</P>
<P>
He said that another factor hindering progress was the low
private and foreign direct investment (FDI) flows to African
countries.
</P>
<P>
"Most FDI flows are going to those countries that are already
rich and developed and very little is going to the poor and
underdeveloped countries that need those resources the most," he
added, citing that unfortunately only one percent of FDI is
flowing to Africa at present.
</P>
<P>
Kikwete also called for public participation in environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
"Education and public awareness programs can change attitudes
and produce more sustainable environmentally friendly life
styles," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference was attended by experts from Zambia,
Kenya, Malawi, Nigeria and Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
