<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's White Farmers Organize Eviction of Veterans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Some white commercial farmers in
Mashonaland Central Province in north Zimbabwe are mobilizing
their workers and the supporters of the opposition Movement for
Democratic Change (MDC) to drive out war veterans and villagers
occupying farms in the area, The Sunday Mail quoted the police as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The former freedom fighters have occupied about 1,500 white
farms since February this year to press for accelerating land
redistribution and President Robert Mugabe has refused to
intervene in the farm invasion.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Police Commissioner responsible for crime and operations
 Griffiths Mpofu said on Saturday that on Friday farmers had
organized their workers and MDC supporters to attack war veterans
at Ceres Farm in Shamva.
</P>
<P>
Relating to the incident, Mpofu said a lorry from Ceres farm in
Shamva had ferried the workers to where war veterans and some
villagers camped within the farm.
</P>
<P>
Five people had then taken some whips from the car and attacked
the war veterans, forcing them to flee.
</P>
<P>
"During the disturbance, the occupants of the Nissan Sunny
(car) were shouting that the war veterans must go back to their
homes and that there was no reason why they should remain in the
farms because the MDC was also now in Parliament," said the Deputy
Commissioner.
</P>
<P>
He said it was sad to note that the farmers were now involved
in mobilizing their workers and some youths to forcibly evict
those occupying the commercial farms.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to warn some elements within the commercial
farms never to take the law into their own hands. The police are
ready on the ground and anybody who is attacked should report," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the police have arrested 24 youths in Harare as they
step up efforts to quell post-election violence.
</P>
<P>
There were fears that political violence could resurface in
some parts of the country this weekend as the candidates who won
in the June 24 and 25 parliamentary elections celebrate their
victory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
