<HEADLINE> Kenya Closes over 400 Illegal Clinics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Over 400 clinics, pharmacies and
laboratories operating illegally and with ill-trained staff in
Kenya have been shut down over the past six months, Kenyan
Minister for Medical Health Amukowa Anangwe has revealed.
</P>
<P>
The official newspaper the Herald on Sunday quoted the minister
as saying 130 owners of such premises had been convicted for
drug-related offences and fined a total of 280,000 shillings
(about 3,400 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"In Nairobi alone, the exercise revealed the majority of the
offenders are operating in premises which are either unregistered
or not licensed," he said.
</P>
<P>
Anangwe said new laws will be established to check malpractice
in this domain because the existing regulatory measures are
inherently weak.
</P>
<P>
He added that his ministry has proposed stringent and deterrent
 penalties for offenders under the Miscellaneous Bill 2000 that
will pursue vigorous drug sector reforms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
