<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Education News in China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China will complete its reform of higher education within the
coming five years, the Ministry of Education (MOE) announced on
June 27.
</P>
<P>
The reform primarily aims to nurture quality personnel who have
both creative spirit and practical ability so that university
teaching skills will be improved.
</P>
<P>
Through the reform, the MOE hopes to open a number of new
courses, add teaching materials and software, establish several
outstanding teaching bases, train an army of highly qualified
teachers, and set up an appraisal system of teaching in higher
education.
</P>
<P>
 30 Chinese Colleges Provide Long-Distance Education
</P>
<P>
Chinese Education Ministry has approved 30 universities and
colleges to conduct long-distance education.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry has also decided to invest 40 million yuan (about
4.8 million US dollars) in college network education.
</P>
<P>
The aim for the development of modern long-distance education
in China is to form an open education network and to build up a
life education system, said an official from the Department of
Higher Learning of the Ministry.
</P>
<P>
 Education Forum: Integrating IT into Education
</P>
<P>
Efforts must be made to integrate information technology (IT)
into education for all, an education professor from Beijing
University told the China Basic Education Forum on June 28.
</P>
<P>
Gao Liming pointed out that in modern-day society, IT has an
important role to play in education, including decision making,
sustainable development of education, and assistance and training
programs for teachers.
</P>
<P>
Though application of IT in education requires huge initial
input, it will improve the quality of education by expanding the
scale and lowering the cost, Gao said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
