<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One-Fourth of Bangladeshi Urban People Live in Slums </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The study on "Needs Assessment Survey of the Disadvantaged
Women and Children in the Urban Areas of Bangladesh," conducted by
Concern Bangladesh, observed that growth of urban slums and spurt
in homeless population are two of the "gravest challenges" the
country is now facing.
</P>
<P>
Covering urban population of Dhaka, Chittagong and other major
towns, the study pointed out some 600,000 more households are
either squatting or homeless, resulting in total homeless
population of 2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
The target population for the survey included socially and
economically disadvantaged women and children, especially sex
workers, the disabled and the street children.
</P>
<P>
The Concern Bangladesh's study said apart from brothel-based
sex workers, 33 percent of the floating women are "mainly engaged
in sex work" as a means of livelihood. The number of such floating
sex workers would "range from 83,000 to 171,000."
</P>
<P>
An earlier study on "Floating People and Slum Population" by
Bangladesh Bureau of Statistics showed that urban population is
increasing by about six percent a year, while the overall
population growth rate is 1.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
