<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denmark, Sweden Linked by Cross-strait Bridge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Sweden and Denmark are now linked,
with a 16-kilometer bridge-and-tunnel project, which was opened to
traffic on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Danish Queen Margrethe and Swedish King Carl Gustaf officially
inaugurated the project in a ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The 18-billion-Finnish mark (3.7-billion-U.S. dollar) project,
which includes an auto-rail bridge, an artificial island in mid-
strait and a four-kilometer underwater tunnel, will carry
automotive vehicles and trains across the Oresund Strait between
the Danish capital of Copenhagen and Malmoe, Sweden's third-
largest city.
</P>
<P>
It is hoped that the connection will boost trade between
Scandinavia's south and the European continent proper.
</P>
<P>
Travelers are expected to increase fivefold to 10,000 per day,
as they can cross the strait in about 20 minutes by car, as
against one hour by ferry.
</P>
<P>
The project is the third largest in Europe after the Channel
Tunnel and Denmark's Stora Baelt bridge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000702.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolian Parliamentary Elections Begin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, July 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 1.2 million registered
Mongolian voters began streaming to some 1,600 polling stations
across the country Sunday morning to cast their ballots in the
country's third parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
A total of 579 candidates representing 13 political parties and
three blocs, as 24 well 24 independents, are contesting 76 seats
in the State Great Khural, the parliament.
</P>
<P>
In rural areas, some herdsmen have to travel up to 100
kilometers to reach the nearest station before the poll ends at 10
p.m. (1400 GMT). The polling stations were opened at 7 a.m. (2300
GMT Saturday).
</P>
<P>
Preliminary results are expected to be released Monday
afternoon and the official results will be announced some 10 days
later.
</P>
<P>
The latest opinion poll has shown that the opposition Mongolian
People's Revolutionary Party (MPRP) is expected to win 51 percent
of the vote, far ahead of the ruling coalition's major partners --
the Mongolian National Democratic Party and the Mongolian Social
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
The MPRP, the country's largest opposition, won 25 seats in
last parliamentary elections four years ago, compared with a 50-
seat majority held by the ruling four-party coalition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
