<HEADLINE> U.N. Special Envoy Mediating in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A special envoy of U.N. Secretary-
General Kofi Annan is currently here to seek way for bringing
about dialogue between the government and the opposition to settle
the country's present political crisis.
</P>
<P>
Razali Ismail, who arrived here on Thursday, has met with First
Secretary of the ruling State Peace and Development Council
Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt and Foreign Minister U Win Aung as
well as General Secretary of the opposition National League for
Democracy (NLD) Aung San Suu Kyi.
</P>
<P>
So far, there is no official disclosure of the details of the
meetings.
</P>
<P>
Razali is also expected to meet other political party leaders.
</P>
<P>
Razali's visit followed the one to Myanmar made in October 1999
by Alvaro de Soto, the then special envoy of the U.N. secretary-
general.
</P>
<P>
In May 1990, a general election was held by the present Myanmar
military government which took over the power of state in
September 1988.
</P>
<P>
In the election, the NLD won the majority of the parliamentary
seats with 396 or 82 percent out of the total 485.
</P>
<P>
The NLD complains that although 10 years have passed, the
election result has not yet materialized.
</P>
<P>
Beginning in late 1997, the government and the NLD tried for
several times in vain to have their leaders meet formally, as the
government insisted on excluding Aung San Suu Kyi from the meeting,
while the NLD stuck to her inclusion.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has repeatedly stressed that it is a
caretaker or transitional government and has no intention to hold
on to power for long. 
</P>
</TEXT>
