<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China Strengthens Protection of Forestry Resources
</P>
<P>
The State Forestry Administration (SFA) launched a nationwide
forest protection campaign to crack down on destruction of forest
resources.
</P>
<P>
The administration will work with law-enforcement agencies and
local authorities to investigate major cases of illegal logging,
woodland abuse and poaching of the endangered animals, deputy SFA
director Zhou Shengxian said.
</P>
<P>
China to Increase Precipitation for Dry Northwest China:
Official
</P>
<P>
China plans to use artificial rainfall method to increase
precipitation for its vast but dry northwest China in central Asia,
the country's top meteorological official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Wen Kegang, director of the China Meteorological Administration,
said artificial rainfall centers will be set up in the Hetao area
between the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region and the Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region, the Tianshan Mountain area in the Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region, and the Hexi Corridor area in Gansu
Province.
</P>
<P>
He said in an interview with Xinhua that a national unified
command and coordination system will also be set up for the
operation of the centers.
</P>
<P>
 China Set to Beat Man-made Deserts
</P>
<P>
China will take measures to fight against man-made deserts
created by human neglect of prairies and farmland.
</P>
<P>
The desert control program, the largest of its kind since 1949,
is made up of 11 sub-projects to be carried out in more than 400
counties of 14 provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities in
north and northwest China.
</P>
<P>
This year China will allocate 12 billion yuan (about 1.45
billion U.S. dollars) to stave off desertification, launching
large-scale tree planting and air-seeding campaigns over the man-
made deserts.
</P>
<P>
China to Close Down 50 Polluting Small Steelworks
</P>
<P>
China announced Thursday the first group of 50 small steelworks
to be closed down this year.
</P>
<P>
An official with the State Administration of Metallurgical
Industry (SAMI) said China plans to shut down 225 small steelworks
in the next few years, and has set this year's target at 103.
</P>
<P>
A total of 3.58 million tons of out-dated steel production
capacity will be eliminated by the end of the year, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 1,000 unqualified steel plants, with an
annual production exceeding 5 million tons. These mills are
generally heavy polluters and high energy consumers, and their
products are of a low quality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
