<HEADLINE> Chinese Environment News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sino-German Afforestation Program Fruitful
</P>
<P>
Some 20,000 hectares of forest have been grown with the Sino-
German afforestation program in central China's Dongting Lake Area,
accounting for 65 percent of the set task.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the program was formally launched
by Hunan Province and the German Bank of Reconstruction in
February 1998.
</P>
<P>
Germany provided a grant of 12 million DM for the project which
will be carried out in eight years.
</P>
<P>
China to Curb Pollution in Great Canal
</P>
<P>
The Hangzhou city government in east China's Zhejiang province
will invest four billion yuan (480 million U.S. dollars) to curb
pollution in the southernmost section of the Beijing-Hangzhou
Great Canal.
</P>
<P>
The government has worked out a plan to curb pollution and
remove unsightly buildings along an 18.1-km river section in
Hangzhou, capital of the Province.
</P>
<P>
The river has been heavily polluted by industrial oil and
garbage.
</P>
<P>
 Anti-Locust Campaign Effective
</P>
<P>
China is taking effective measures to control plagues of
locusts, according to sources from the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
A total of 466,700 hectares of farmland hit by oriental
grasshoppers have already been brought under control in the
provinces of Hebei, Shandong, Henan, Anhui, Shanxi, Shaanxi and
Jiangsu as well as in Tianjin Municipality, accounting for 65
percent of the locust-stricken land.
</P>
<P>
Ministry sources said that about two thirds of the locusts have
been eradicated in the worst-hit areas in Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Artificial Rain Eases Drought in NE China
</P>
<P>
People in northeast China's Liaoning Province experienced a
delightful rain this weekend after almost two weeks of sweltering
heat.
</P>
<P>
Two cloud-seeding helicopters flew for ten hours Saturday,
spraying silver iodide into a cold air mass moved from the west
into the province. As a result, 14 cities in the area received
moderate to heavy rain, and some regions in the province even had
heavy storms, which lessened the serious drought in over one
million ha of dried land.
</P>
<P>
However, the local meteorological bureau warned that the
artificial rain will not solve the drought problem, as the water
supply in most reservoirs has not reached the necessary level.
</P>
<P>
Farmers Along Yangtze Contract to Grow Trees
</P>
<P>
More than 1.27 million rural families in 120 counties at the
upper reaches of the Yangtze River have signed contracts with the
local governments to convert low-yielding farmland into tree belts
and pastures.
</P>
<P>
China will give free grain to farmers who reforest their own
land, as the country has ample grain reserves thanks to years of
good harvests. The state will be responsible for the maintenance
of the saplings and trees.
</P>
</TEXT>
