<HEADLINE> Sampras Rallies Back to Win Third Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Pete Sampras of
the United States rallied from first set down to beat fellow
American Justin Gimselstob 2-6, 6-4, 6-2 and 6-2 at the Wimbledon
tennis championships on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, ignoring left leg injury, appeared on the brink of his
first Wimbledon defeat since 1996 when he lost the first set with
hardly a whimper. His serve, the base on which his six singles
titles were founded, was misfiring and he looked totally dejected.
</P>
<P>
But the 28-year-old top seed decided to play himself out of
trouble and he was back to his best by the time he swept past
Gimelstob to set up a last 16 match with unseeded Swede Jonas
Bjorkman.
</P>
<P>
Fourth seed Gustavo Kuerten, suffering from a heavy cold,
succumbed to big-hitting German Alexander Popp 7-6, 6-2, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
Australian Patrick Rafter, a semifinalist last year, went
through 6-2, 7-6, 6-3 against another German, Rainer Schuettler,
while second seed Andre Agassi, who had to save two matchpoints in
his previous match, had no such problems in beating France's
Jerome Golmard 6-3, 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Of this year's top seven men's seeds, Agassi and Sampras are
the only two left.
</P>
<P>
As evening fell, Mark Philippoussis, seeded 10th, reached the
last 16 after winning the longest fifth set in a Grand Slam since
1968.
</P>
<P>
The Australian beat Sjeng Schalken 4-6, 6-3, 6-7, 7-6, 20-18 in
a five-hour match of high tension. Dutchman Schalken was also
involved in the longest match of last year's championships which
he lost to Jim Courier.
</P>
<P>
Defending women's champion Lindsay Davenport reached the last
16, where she meets fellow American Jennifer Capriati, after
beating Argentine Paola Suarez 6-4, 6-2. Monica Seles, with the
minimum of fuss, defeated Sarah Pitkowski of France 6-0, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
The sixth seed now plays another veteran campaigner, Arantxa
Sanchez-Vicario, for the first time on grass after the ninth-
seeded Spaniard saved two matchpoints in beating Sandra Nacuk of
Yugoslavia 3-6, 7-6, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's drama on the most famous court in the world came
just minutes after more than 60 of Wimbledon's former champions
and finalists had taken part in a parade.
</P>
<P>
Fifth seed Venus Williams beat Nathalie Dechy of 6-0, 7-6 to
join her sister Serena in the last 16. She now plays Sabine
Appelmans of Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Australian Jelena Dokic, famous for her tempestuous father and
last year's first-round defeat of Martina Hingis, showed she was
no one-hit wonder by beating American Brie Rippner 6-2, 6-1. Dokic
will next play American Kristina Brandi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
