<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Market Goods Globally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Mauritian Prime Minister
Navichndra Ramgoolam Saturday urged African countries to trade
more amongst themselves and take advantage of the new trade
investment legislation of the United States to trade more on the
global market.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of this year's Zambia
international trade fair in Ndola, Copperbelt Province, Ramgoolam
said there was need for African countries and COMESA members in
particular to trade more among themselves.
</P>
<P>
Ramgoolam, also current chairman of the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA), said African countries were
rich in resources and produce abundant goods which should be
shared among themselves.
</P>
<P>
With abundant resources and products, he said Africa was set to
compete with the best in the world.
</P>
<P>
"Let's take advantage of the new trade and investment
legislation of the United States government known as the trade and
development act 2000 to trade more on the global market.
</P>
<P>
"The new act has opened new partnerships between the United
States and Africa," he told the participants including Zambian
President Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Ramgoolam said the new legislation has also opened new trade
opportunities for Africa to do more business with the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
"The more we trade on the global market the more we shall
improve the quality of life of our people," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that lack of information about Africa's
products to the international market, was a hindrance to exporting
its goods.
</P>
<P>
"Africa needs to market itself well by making its products
known to the global market. There are many good things about
Africa but these remain unknown to the outside world. With the new
United States legislation, we need to sell our continent and
maximize the use of the new act 2000," Ramgoolam said.
</P>
<P>
He called on COMESA countries to remove impediments towards
achieving free intra-COMESA trade by October 31 this year, saying
his government has reduced duty on 1,500 products.
</P>
<P>
"We must remove impediments towards free trade in COMESA. To do
this, we need sacrifices," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Chiluba, Ramgoolam will return to Zambia in
October this year to launch COMESA free trade area (FTA) in
Lusaka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
