<HEADLINE> Universities In Africa Challenged To Speak out on Truth, Justice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Vice Chancellor of Swaziland
University Lydia Phindile Makhubu has challenged universities in
Africa to speak out in support of truth and justice to awaken the
conscience of the society.
</P>
<P>
Officiating at the graduation of 265 students at Africa
University, 25 kilometers away from Mutare in east Zimbabwe on
Saturday, Makhubu said Africa, as a society, was in a state of
crisis and unable to confront moral issues and to distinguish
between the right and the wrong.
</P>
<P>
She said it was the duty of universities to produce students
who will conscientize the society towards the consolidation of
human rights, democracy and peace.
</P>
<P>
"Institutions of higher learning are being challenged more than
ever before to speak out in support of truth and justice in a
continent where such are easily compromised," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said universities must accord students with academic
freedom at campus so that they would be able to speak out on all
issues that affect the society.
</P>
<P>
She said while most universities were facing pressure to expand
and increase enrolment, many institutions in southern Africa had
embarked on a noble idea of establishing long distance education
programs to accommodate all needy cases.
</P>
<P>
She said if the long distance program was fully explored, it
would expand access to education and increase university
stakeholder.
</P>
<P>
The graduation is the sixth since the opening of the university
in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
